A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners are struggling to find the money needed to repair declining highway infrastructure, many are envisioning a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches itself above your car’s dashboard.
The devices, which record every mile travelled by a motorist and transmit the information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government planning offices to rework the outdated system of financing major U.S. roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major axes planning has suddenly provoked heated debate and hectic alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to pressure the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly the road you travel, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The tea party is terrified.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress cannot agree on whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to move to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental ride.
This is really essential for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, director general of the Southern California Association of Governments, which expects the state to start recording the miles each California motorist has traveled by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded with taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don’t buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more than miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by one cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The gas tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently had trackers installed on 500 cars to test a mile-long payment system.
“It turns out to be the most logical alternative in the long run,” he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage usage fee.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to city liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state’s ambitious laws on global warming.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also considers it the most viable alternative in the long term.
The free market supporters of the Reason Foundation also appreciate the idea of making drivers pay for the mile.
“It’s not just a tax going into a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they receive.
The move is also backed by two former U.S. transport secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go the way of mile payment.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have covered about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural lawmakers representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to work or to town.
However, several states and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the most important experience in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state mileage fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is testing a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the U.S. east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is studying how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their cars with a device, drivers were concerned that the government could follow their every move.
“Anxiety about Big Brother and that kind of thing is a big deal,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management in Nevada’s Department of Transportation.
This is not something that people want.
From the beginning of the test, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: "It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged locators."
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people’s daily goings and goings.
Nevada is one of the few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small California start-up called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to help motorists who pay taxes to states.
It was looking to break into the emerging car insurance market, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices she tests liked big-axis planners because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, downloaded periodically by modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Big mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much less expensive ways and much less intrusive methods to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles traveled by all state residents.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transport officials are looking to develop a taxation scheme that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide “pay-to-drive” insurance, and create a real-time speed dataset from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Motorists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits the system offers them," said a document on urban development.
However, some transport planners are wondering if the whole mile-payment debate isn't just a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be imposed on hybrid vehicle drivers and others whose vehicles do not consume much gasoline, so that each pays his fair share.
“There is no need to resort to radical surgery when you simply need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, the commission’s director of legislation and public affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: Four Unreleased Listening
The English musician has not finished surprising this year.
Starting with The Next Day, which was released in January, he concocted a luxury reissue scheduled for November 4, with several unreleased.
Four have already emerged on the web.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone panicked.
On his 66th birthday, on January 8, 2013, he said a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dated 2003) and too few public appearances, the English musician proved that we could still rely on him to sparkle the pop scene.
A feast for your fans
Not tired of the surprises, David Bowie had more than one round in his bag with The Next Day.
The Thin White Duke will re-release the album on November 4.
For the occasion, he concocted a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, titled The Next Day Extra, will feature three discs: the original album, unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four previously unveiled clips.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks from the Deluxe Edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie also made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces at the same time each of the records, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and covers, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And, most importantly, he gives a taste of his new title Atomica, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with guitars far ahead and a rock electricity skillfully mastered.
Unpublished already listening
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the web.
The Informer is double-sided: a disturbing intro before a luminous cavalcade that gradually slows down to make way for a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a small reference to Elton John's Rocket Man, or even Gravity?
With this cheerful title, the singer seems at least in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again makes reference to his strangeness: would he come from another planet?
The guitar riffs, bewitching, make you want to leave the Earth.
Bowie has fun playing chameleon with these titles: turn informant, man on board a rocket, potential Martian...
He hides and reveals at the same time, plays adopting different personalities, as he has throughout his career, including with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
It is no surprise that he has a mask in his hand in the photography of the campaign L'Invitation au Voyage, of the brand Louis Vuitton, whose new face he embodies.
It will appear in one of their commercials, broadcast from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that the wounded soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was being followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Nicholson assured that before their release, members of the military were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All wounded soldiers receive appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them are released until they are ready, he said.
Detractors accuse the government of wanting to save money by failing to allow injured military personnel - who do not comply with the army's "universality of service" rule requiring staff to be able to perform a variety of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for retirement benefits.
