Frontier Airlines plans to pay for hand baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for passengers carrying hand luggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for a coffee or soda, although in its announcement Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them on the plane's descent.
The new hand baggage charges apply to bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if fees were paid in advance and $100 if travelers only paid once at the boarding gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O’Malley said the $100 was planned to encourage travelers to pay the fees in advance.
“We don’t want to pay that price,” she said.
Airlines began charging for first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid these charges put as many things as they could in the hand luggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no room in those compartments.
These fees are a way to ensure that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley said that these new fees won't really be used to raise money.
It’s about making Frontier’s most loyal customers understand that it’s becoming increasingly difficult to find room in the upper compartments.
Passengers who buy their ticket on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
Thus, a passenger queuing at a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and check-in procedures are changing to ensure that passengers are aware of these charges before they arrive at the gate.
Frontier’s hand baggage charges will not apply until the summer, although no date has been set.
Passengers often groan about baggage and other fees, but airlines love them.
They believe that baggage handling costs are significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street see the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines are charging enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, many of them did not cover the baggage costs.
Spirit Airlines Inc. applied the first hand baggage charges three years ago, and the low-cost airline Allegiant followed suit a little later.
The only other airline imposing such charges is Hungarian airline Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely tracks the charges in addition.
In a December 2011 report, he estimated that Spirit’s hand luggage costs were $50 million per year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently traveled on Spirit and wondered what he was going to find at the boarding gate when passengers discovered unusual hand luggage charges imposed by the company.
“I’ve never seen such a smooth boarding procedure in my entire professional career,” he said.
I was expecting to see grinding teeth and a fight breaking out at the door.
The plane was full, he added, “passengers got on board at the speed of lightning.”
Frontier also does as Spirit and applies a $2 fee for a coffee, tea, soda or fruit juice.
Frontier said passengers who take a soda or fruit juice can take the unopened can with them, and those who drink coffee can be reserved for free.
She will always distribute water for free.
US Airways briefly attempted to charge for drinks in 2008 but went back seven months later after passengers complained and while no other major airline had followed.
