How biometrics will invade our lives
Are you done typing passwords to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will make it possible to assure the identity of a person carrying out transactions in a universe as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Privacy organizations confirm this craze for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
In 2011 alone and in France, the Commission Nationale de l’Informatique et des Libertés authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques that will deliver new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its constraints.
"For example, some people who work with concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity domain at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - one cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a drawback: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been carried out for about twenty years on other approaches, such as face recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
By increasing the accuracy of the sensors and the computing capacity of the computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, according to Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and Holland have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we’re doing research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but it takes a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and unfalsifiable marker, DNA also arouses hope and concern.
"At the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, director of studies, innovation and foresight at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they claim to be).
The identification has hitherto concerned the issuance of identity papers: it is necessary to compare the biometric elements (imprints, photo, iris) with the information that the State has about all citizens already registered.
This ensures that one person does not attempt to impersonate someone else.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance to a hotel or store.
“We retrieve the images from the surveillance cameras and compare them to the photos of celebrities who are freely circulating on the Internet,” said Dany Nassif, NEC France’s Business Development Manager for Biometric Identification Solutions.
Another use: take a photo of a quidam queuing in a store, track his progress with facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially involved physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, presence control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend pointing for another," justifies Cyrille Bataller, Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those carried out from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some ATMs by inserting your card and placing your hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the keying of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in stores with their bank card, the customer does not type their code, but inserts their finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in checkout thirty seconds shorter, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you tailor-made options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people's identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which crashes if one tries to move it," says Philippe Robin, of Thales.
But in the absence of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
Privacy specialists, on the other hand, continue to be concerned.
“The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” predicts Andrew Patrick, of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
