Scientists have just shed light on how the movements of a dog’s tail are related to his mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs moved their tails more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved their tails more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what was going on with other species.
He added that, just like in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disorderly tail movements of other dogs, the researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the animals’ heart rate and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won’t take long before we understand why their tails sometimes go to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with films featuring other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor – and we were able to manipulate the tail movement and present it as going more left or right.”
When the animals saw an expressionless dog shaking the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog shaking the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail deflecting mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the tail-swinging dog), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience what movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: “If you meet other dogs repeatedly and notice that most of the time, the movement of their tails to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
The researchers say the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canine behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs would go to a robot dog more easily when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study.”
He indicated that the differences could come from the fact that the dogs participating in the different studies did not fully consider film animals or robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“Although many evidence, found in different mammals, indicates that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it probably won’t take long before we understand why their tails sometimes move on one side and sometimes on the other.
