Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents her two new group choreographies at Danse Danse: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second infused by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies de Satie.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from ink black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, also white, in the immense space that is the Thé<0xC3><0xA2>tre Maisonneuve, advances, profile, thin as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, a simple line, takes its shape.
And this shape will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, only the hands and face uncovered, wait on either side of the playground, rush when the next script appears, embody it, come out running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is done in relays of solos, in group in unison (a mass that makes solo), in large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
One thinks of "Glory of the Morning", where, solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, posed online at the front stage.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace always fast.
There will be breakage when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux's poem, monotone and monotonous in the auction, and will continue dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to resume.
This sound and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are a few beautiful flashes - the creation of images has always been a force at Chouinard - such as those hairs that scuffle or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet the work of Michaux, has prevailed, with her tics.
The result: the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’s inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a wider and more giddy imaginary than dance, more porous.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers chopped by a strobe light and white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches magic.
The audience liked it, the welcome was warm.
Gymnopedias, after the intermission, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in gray, the dancers and a piano are covered in fabrics, like furniture in an abandoned house.
On the piano, dancers relay themselves to play the scores.
Their awkwardness in music, touching, gives a real fragility.
On stage, couples pass, in loving duos, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small solos of transitions, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffoons appear, also familiar with Chouinard, with a red nose, in highly polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnassists, fugitives or gamblers.
The gesture, the laughter and the small cries beautifully transpose the archaic, the grace and ridicule of the bodies in coitus, of the beings that merge.
But the play takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown comes back on stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the universes explored overlap, the dancers cabotine, descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a disorder cleverly calculated that remains sensual.
Joy and madness perspire, and it's Chouinard's art there to contaminate the public.
