Yesterday, Barack Obama adjusted his original promise.
“The vast majority of people with the right health insurance can keep it,” he said in a speech in Boston.
Speaking of what he calls "a buzz in the news" about the terminations, President Obama has incited Americans who were receiving the notices to seek new insurance in the market.
Most people will be able to get comprehensive and better suited health plans for the same price, or even for even less than expected.
“You will win,” he said.
The Administration announced that it should come as no surprise if the 5% of the population who self-insured are forced to change plans because their coverage does not meet the new standards required under the Affordable Care Act.
“Let me speak directly to these Americans: you deserve better,” Kathleen Sebelius told the Energy and Trade Committee in Washington.
Sebelius, who oversees the implementation of the Affordable Care Act, said the launch of the online marketplace in October had failed "unfortunately".
“I’m as frustrated and irritated as anyone,” she added.
I look forward to regaining your confidence.
It was an exasperated Kathleen Sebelius who uttered this sentence, as she believed her microcoupe, addressing an assistant sitting behind her at yesterday’s Assembly session following an exchange of contentious views with Republican Representative Billy Long of Missouri, about whether she should join Obamacare.
For more than three hours, Billy Long insisted on asking Mrs. Sebelius why the Affordable Care Act “architect” hadn’t voluntarily given up government-sponsored insurance to take out a plan via HealthCare.gov, which she now boasts to millions of Americans.
Vettel launches special helmet in Abu Dhabi
The lucky elect, Jake Vite Prekop, combined the colors of the car brand and the German flag, while integrating the notions of speed and heat at the track level.
The German Sebastian Vettel, four-time Formula 1 World Champion, on Friday released a special helmet designed by a 21-year-old Mexican fan for free trials at the Abu Dhabi Grand Prix.
Vettel has chosen from among 1,500 drawings sent from around the world, as part of a competition launched by one of the sponsors, a car brand, of his team.
He was invited to follow the Abu Dhabi GP, with a friend, and can therefore see the German champion up close, on the track and in his booth.
Vettel had to wear this helmet on Friday and Saturday, for testing.
It is likely that he will have another special helmet on Sunday, for the race, destined to mark his fourth consecutive world title.
A resident of Aubervilliers launches his Party of the suburbs
Let us not be mistaken.
In the spirit of Abdel-Malik Djermoune, its founder, the "Party of the suburbs" is not only aimed at suburban residents.
I chose a map of France as the logo, he justifies.
When I speak of suburbs, I speak to all those who are excluded from the great national family.
However, his project, presented Thursday at a press conference in his native town of Aubervilliers, was born from the desire to better defend multiculturalism, this great cultural melting pot that characterizes above all the neighborhoods.
My first proposal is to create a ministry of multiculturalism, he says.
Abdel-Malik Djermoune, 50, a territorial attaché, today claims to be "100% apolitical" even if he has not always been neutral.
Militant in 2002 alongside Jean-Pierre Chevénement, he then supported locally Dominique de Villepin between 2010 and 2011.
I know that the values of equality that I advocate in my program are linked to the left, but if the people on the right are willing to support me, I will listen to them, too.
It is only extremist parties that I am not talking about.
In addition to multiculturalism, Abdel-Malik Djermoune has built his programme -consultable on the Internet- from many themes supposed to speak to the inhabitants of the suburbs and in particular to the young: the right to vote for foreigners, the legalization of cannabis, the civil majority at 16 years of age, the rehabilitation of the function of custodian of buildings...
There remains to be candidates to form lists and defend his ideas on the political stage."For the 2014 municipal elections, this may be fair, he acknowledges."
It is a problem of time and money.
The Party of the suburbs should still be represented in Aubervilliers through my candidacy and I hope also in other cities.
Abdel-Malik Djermoune says he already has seven heads in metropolitan France and Martinique.
"And the support emails that I have received since yesterday do not all come from suburban areas," he said.
John Kerry admitted, unprecedentedly, that American espionage “has gone too far inappropriately.”
John Kerry indicated a softening of the U.S.' defensive attitude toward its surveillance programs by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions espionage "has gone too far inappropriately."
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, ruled on “automatic pilot” when a series of incendiary revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about NSA espionage activities emerged.
The leaks have put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London by video link, Mr. Kerry said: “It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government learned about certain things in autopilot mode because we had the opportunity to do so, from the Second World War and up to the difficult years of the Cold War, and then, of course, 9/11.”
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed the line, but insisted that everyone's rights had not been violated.
He said, “In some cases, it went too far inappropriately.”
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make clear to the people that he was now conducting a thorough review of these practices so that no one would feel mistaken.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We live in a new world where people are ready to be blown up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we were able to learn the facts in advance.
In the meantime, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. spying case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the U.S., the chairman of the Senate subcommittee on European affairs said on Thursday.
Sen. Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had made about a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations due to the sense of frustration aroused by the National Security Agency's surveillance.
“It’s really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans stay with us in mutual commitment in the fight against terrorism,” Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chairman of the U.S. Senate’s subcommittee on European affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
And I will go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger provoked by NSA programs.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has undermined relations with some of the U.S. allies, however the agency's director said this week that it was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding because it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the U.S.
Other revelations have revealed documents released by Snowden that the NSA intercepted data and communications from German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone and those of 34 other heads of state.
The director of intelligence, James Clapper, justified the espionage of the allies by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this atmosphere of tumult, Murphy said his office was organizing a congressional trip, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hoped the delegation would include members of both parties and both houses.
The names of the other participating legislators are expected to be released in the coming days.
He said the route remains to be defined.
Murphy said the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show “loving firmness.”
He explained that European heads of state must be honest with their citizens about the type of spying programs they have been implementing themselves for years.
“We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world who spy,” Murphy said.
In the meantime, Kerry plans to travel this weekend to the Middle East and Poland to manage the grudge generated by US strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as by US surveillance activities.
