Living together in French, the challenge of the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board
At the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board, 62% of students have a mother tongue other than French.
This is what motivated a year ago, a consultation with parents, students, teachers and education staff, to think about ways to better integrate students who live on horseback between different cultures.
The school board has just unveiled its vision of "Living Together in French".
Vision Diversity has been walking schools for the past year to help students of all backgrounds discover common benchmarks that are not limited to the French language.
The discovery of neighborhoods, our architecture, our places are landmarks.
Great names of writers, artists, whether they are of origin or they came from elsewhere.
Who are our builders?
“So we create projects so that they identify with all of this,” says Vision Diversity President Aida Kamar.
Michel Venne, from the Institut du Nouveau Monde, identified several challenges for the school board.
"On the transmission, for example, of what Quebec culture is, the sense of belonging, the support to staff in the transformations that we are experiencing, within the student clientele," he lists.
The Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board has created a research centre that will provide tools for teachers who, at times, also come from elsewhere.
Rachida Azdouz, from the University of Montreal, will be the scientific director.
Preparing to manage a class in a North American, Quebec context.
"Different pedagogical strategies, that's the real need," she summarizes.
Research will focus on inclusion from all angles: linguistic, educational, social and cultural.
